WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.460 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:02.460 --> 00:00:18.845 align:middle line:90%


00:00:18.845 --> 00:00:20.970 align:middle line:10%
>>GEORGE NOORY: Well, if
you watch Gaia Television,

00:00:20.970 --> 00:00:23.345 align:middle line:10%
you're going to know this
fellow I'm about to introduce--

00:00:23.345 --> 00:00:26.640 align:middle line:10%
Ben Stewart, a world-renowned
musician, filmmaker,

00:00:26.640 --> 00:00:30.900 align:middle line:10%
speaker on spiritual ascension,
super-human potential,

00:00:30.900 --> 00:00:32.430 align:middle line:10%
and self-discovery.

00:00:32.430 --> 00:00:34.680 align:middle line:84%
He's got some great
films and documentaries,

00:00:34.680 --> 00:00:36.300 align:middle line:90%
which we'll get into as well.

00:00:36.300 --> 00:00:37.890 align:middle line:90%
Ben, welcome to Beyond Belief.

00:00:37.890 --> 00:00:38.330 align:middle line:90%
>>BEN STEWART: Thank you.

00:00:38.330 --> 00:00:39.371 align:middle line:90%
It's an honor to be here.

00:00:39.371 --> 00:00:41.070 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: This is very
different for me.

00:00:41.070 --> 00:00:43.980 align:middle line:84%
Because you're a
musician by trade,

00:00:43.980 --> 00:00:47.130 align:middle line:84%
spent years in the Air Force,
and now you're dealing with

00:00:47.130 --> 00:00:48.720 align:middle line:90%
this-- what I would call--

00:00:48.720 --> 00:00:51.450 align:middle line:84%
super-humanism and
transformation.

00:00:51.450 --> 00:00:55.065 align:middle line:84%
How did you make that
evolutionary turn.

00:00:55.065 --> 00:00:58.380 align:middle line:10%
>>STEWART: Really, the
evolution found me.

00:00:58.380 --> 00:01:02.070 align:middle line:10%
I've always been into working
out and exercise, and elevating

00:01:02.070 --> 00:01:04.010 align:middle line:10%
the mind and cognition.

00:01:04.010 --> 00:01:06.488 align:middle line:84%
The military-- I wasn't able
to speak out about things,

00:01:06.488 --> 00:01:08.613 align:middle line:84%
as part of being in the
military service, you know.

00:01:08.613 --> 00:01:08.790 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yes, sir.

00:01:08.790 --> 00:01:09.840 align:middle line:90%
No, sir.

00:01:09.840 --> 00:01:10.640 align:middle line:90%
>>STEWART: Mhm.

00:01:10.640 --> 00:01:12.540 align:middle line:10%
As soon as I got
out, I was in a band.

00:01:12.540 --> 00:01:14.460 align:middle line:10%
And I started speaking
out about everything

00:01:14.460 --> 00:01:16.740 align:middle line:10%
I was seeing in the
world in the band.

00:01:16.740 --> 00:01:18.020 align:middle line:90%
And then I started--

00:01:18.020 --> 00:01:19.480 align:middle line:90%
basically, I got really sick.

00:01:19.480 --> 00:01:20.760 align:middle line:90%
I lost a lot of weight.

00:01:20.760 --> 00:01:24.030 align:middle line:84%
And I had to rethink
what health was to me.

00:01:24.030 --> 00:01:26.280 align:middle line:84%
So the more I started looking
into different avenues

00:01:26.280 --> 00:01:28.740 align:middle line:84%
of real health, it
was also getting

00:01:28.740 --> 00:01:30.070 align:middle line:90%
into the health of the mind.

00:01:30.070 --> 00:01:31.560 align:middle line:84%
And when I started
piecing together

00:01:31.560 --> 00:01:33.570 align:middle line:84%
over 20 different
disciplines, it

00:01:33.570 --> 00:01:37.635 align:middle line:84%
started turning into what I now
call the super-human genesis.

00:01:37.635 --> 00:01:41.620 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So you did
this a lot on your own.

00:01:41.620 --> 00:01:42.420 align:middle line:90%
>>STEWART: Yeah.

00:01:42.420 --> 00:01:44.400 align:middle line:90%
Well, actually-- so I'm 34 now.

00:01:44.400 --> 00:01:46.950 align:middle line:84%
When I hit 33,
there was this point

00:01:46.950 --> 00:01:49.439 align:middle line:84%
where I just decided to
learn as much as I could--

00:01:49.439 --> 00:01:50.239 align:middle line:90%


00:01:50.239 --> 00:01:51.829 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You're such
an old man, Ben.

00:01:51.829 --> 00:01:52.629 align:middle line:90%
>>STEWART: I know.

00:01:52.629 --> 00:01:53.850 align:middle line:90%
It's getting to me.

00:01:53.850 --> 00:01:56.460 align:middle line:84%
But I started learning
everything I could--

00:01:56.460 --> 00:02:01.260 align:middle line:84%
spinning fire-- spinning
poi; juggling; hacky sack;

00:02:01.260 --> 00:02:04.880 align:middle line:84%
movement training; ice baths;
and breathing techniques;

00:02:04.880 --> 00:02:08.910 align:middle line:84%
cognition; anything I could do
that was just learning about

00:02:08.910 --> 00:02:09.900 align:middle line:90%
how--

00:02:09.900 --> 00:02:13.095 align:middle line:84%
who I am and how I engage with
the environment around me.

00:02:13.095 --> 00:02:16.650 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Would you say that
most people just don't get it,

00:02:16.650 --> 00:02:18.690 align:middle line:90%
in terms of their own health--

00:02:18.690 --> 00:02:20.520 align:middle line:90%
mental and physical?

00:02:20.520 --> 00:02:23.400 align:middle line:84%
>>STEWART: I say that we get to
a point where we're not sick,

00:02:23.400 --> 00:02:24.450 align:middle line:90%
and we call that health.

00:02:24.450 --> 00:02:27.280 align:middle line:84%
And then nothing
calls us beyond.

00:02:27.280 --> 00:02:30.900 align:middle line:84%
And that's why I'm here, is
because I had nobody really

00:02:30.900 --> 00:02:32.250 align:middle line:90%
calling me beyond.

00:02:32.250 --> 00:02:33.660 align:middle line:90%
I had to--

00:02:33.660 --> 00:02:36.170 align:middle line:84%
I had to get sick for
me to start really

00:02:36.170 --> 00:02:38.550 align:middle line:90%
asking myself, what is health.

00:02:38.550 --> 00:02:40.470 align:middle line:90%
So, I think, a lot of people--

00:02:40.470 --> 00:02:42.330 align:middle line:90%
they get into a comfort zone.

00:02:42.330 --> 00:02:45.480 align:middle line:84%
And that's where they just
kind of stay and they flatline.

00:02:45.480 --> 00:02:49.260 align:middle line:84%
And I'm here to say, our
potential is way up here.

00:02:49.260 --> 00:02:51.659 align:middle line:84%
And we are operating
way down here.

00:02:51.659 --> 00:02:53.200 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And we're
human beings, Ben.

00:02:53.200 --> 00:02:55.680 align:middle line:84%
So we have these ups
and downs in life--

00:02:55.680 --> 00:02:58.380 align:middle line:84%
both physical and
mental, as well.

00:02:58.380 --> 00:03:03.607 align:middle line:84%
How do you keep pushing yourself
to try to stay above that?

00:03:03.607 --> 00:03:05.790 align:middle line:84%
>>STEWART: Really,
it's difficult to say,

00:03:05.790 --> 00:03:07.290 align:middle line:84%
because there is
this inner calling.

00:03:07.290 --> 00:03:09.450 align:middle line:84%
And I do have
moments where I don't

00:03:09.450 --> 00:03:11.280 align:middle line:90%
feel that I'm good enough.

00:03:11.280 --> 00:03:14.010 align:middle line:84%
But, I would say, the best
thing for me is family--

00:03:14.010 --> 00:03:15.440 align:middle line:90%
family and friends.

00:03:15.440 --> 00:03:18.145 align:middle line:84%
I have a beautiful wife and
a beautiful one-year-old

00:03:18.145 --> 00:03:18.945 align:middle line:90%
daughter.

00:03:18.945 --> 00:03:19.810 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Beautiful.

00:03:19.810 --> 00:03:21.390 align:middle line:90%
>>STEWART: And I can't fail.

00:03:21.390 --> 00:03:22.320 align:middle line:90%
So that's what it is.

00:03:22.320 --> 00:03:26.130 align:middle line:84%
I don't have the option
to stay where I'm at.

00:03:26.130 --> 00:03:27.720 align:middle line:84%
I need to keep
developing, because I'm

00:03:27.720 --> 00:03:30.765 align:middle line:84%
setting an example for a little
girl coming into this world.

00:03:30.765 --> 00:03:34.200 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Did you have someone
that you could tap into who

00:03:34.200 --> 00:03:35.850 align:middle line:90%
helped teach you these things?

00:03:35.850 --> 00:03:38.625 align:middle line:84%
Or did you have to do
this all on your own?

00:03:38.625 --> 00:03:40.770 align:middle line:84%
>>STEWART: I would
say everything

00:03:40.770 --> 00:03:44.790 align:middle line:84%
that I've done has to do
with finding individuals

00:03:44.790 --> 00:03:46.950 align:middle line:84%
in different
disciplines, all over.

00:03:46.950 --> 00:03:50.520 align:middle line:84%
And, as I would find them,
they would speak something--

00:03:50.520 --> 00:03:53.280 align:middle line:84%
some form of my
language that I would--

00:03:53.280 --> 00:03:54.810 align:middle line:84%
not fully understand
it, but I would

00:03:54.810 --> 00:03:58.332 align:middle line:84%
know that this is what I
needed to dive into and learn.

00:03:58.332 --> 00:03:59.790 align:middle line:84%
And then, as I
started learning all

00:03:59.790 --> 00:04:01.290 align:middle line:84%
these different
disciplines, I began

00:04:01.290 --> 00:04:03.150 align:middle line:84%
to realize that my
place in all of it

00:04:03.150 --> 00:04:05.790 align:middle line:84%
is not to become the
expert in any one field,

00:04:05.790 --> 00:04:09.360 align:middle line:84%
but to homogenize it, and bring
it into one discipline that

00:04:09.360 --> 00:04:10.992 align:middle line:90%
is super-human ascension.

00:04:10.992 --> 00:04:12.450 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Ben, in
one of your films,

00:04:12.450 --> 00:04:14.340 align:middle line:84%
called "Kymatica,"
you kind of take

00:04:14.340 --> 00:04:17.519 align:middle line:84%
a look at the
separation, the divorce,

00:04:17.519 --> 00:04:21.095 align:middle line:90%
between nature and human beings.

00:04:21.095 --> 00:04:23.220 align:middle line:84%
>>STEWART: An explanation
of our conscious universe

00:04:23.220 --> 00:04:27.450 align:middle line:84%
has been attempted by religion,
science, and philosophy.

00:04:27.450 --> 00:04:30.330 align:middle line:84%
The neglect of biological
nature from any organism

00:04:30.330 --> 00:04:32.585 align:middle line:90%
causes illness.

00:04:32.585 --> 00:04:35.800 align:middle line:84%
A divorce from nature,
exile from Eden,

00:04:35.800 --> 00:04:37.510 align:middle line:90%
confounding of tongues--

00:04:37.510 --> 00:04:41.680 align:middle line:84%
they are all symptoms-- not
of a biblical god, or deity,

00:04:41.680 --> 00:04:43.960 align:middle line:90%
but the true self.

00:04:43.960 --> 00:04:46.630 align:middle line:84%
The greatest and only
threat to ourselves

00:04:46.630 --> 00:04:51.280 align:middle line:84%
is a loss of self, the
death of our divinity.

00:04:51.280 --> 00:04:52.080 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Nice job.

00:04:52.080 --> 00:04:53.962 align:middle line:90%
Now what does kymatica mean?

00:04:53.962 --> 00:04:55.420 align:middle line:84%
>>STEWART: Kymatica
is a Greek term

00:04:55.420 --> 00:04:58.960 align:middle line:84%
for cymatics, which is basically
just the science of sound

00:04:58.960 --> 00:05:01.340 align:middle line:84%
and matter and the
interplay between them.

00:05:01.340 --> 00:05:03.460 align:middle line:84%
So that's-- as a musician,
I love that term.

00:05:03.460 --> 00:05:05.600 align:middle line:84%
But that, to me, is
the entire universe.

00:05:05.600 --> 00:05:07.860 align:middle line:84%
It's all the interplay
between vibration and matter.

00:05:07.860 --> 00:05:09.610 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And when we
separate from nature,

00:05:09.610 --> 00:05:12.187 align:middle line:84%
when we divorce from
nature, what is that?

00:05:12.187 --> 00:05:14.770 align:middle line:84%
>>STEWART: Basically, that means
that we're lost as a species,

00:05:14.770 --> 00:05:16.280 align:middle line:90%
as far as nature is concerned.

00:05:16.280 --> 00:05:19.900 align:middle line:84%
We don't eat natural diets
like our ancestors did.

00:05:19.900 --> 00:05:23.050 align:middle line:84%
We move through flattened
architectural design, not

00:05:23.050 --> 00:05:26.170 align:middle line:84%
the lush and dynamic
nature that we used to.

00:05:26.170 --> 00:05:29.410 align:middle line:84%
And we're also mixing together
social groups quicker,

00:05:29.410 --> 00:05:31.540 align:middle line:90%
with different value groups--

00:05:31.540 --> 00:05:34.520 align:middle line:84%
value systems-- quicker
than we ever have.

00:05:34.520 --> 00:05:36.040 align:middle line:84%
So, basically, put
all that together

00:05:36.040 --> 00:05:39.460 align:middle line:84%
and we have a brand new set of
stressors for the human body

00:05:39.460 --> 00:05:41.680 align:middle line:84%
and the mind to deal
with, that evolution never

00:05:41.680 --> 00:05:42.520 align:middle line:90%
prepared us for.

00:05:42.520 --> 00:05:46.916 align:middle line:84%
So that's the real separation of
nature and where we are today.

00:05:46.916 --> 00:05:49.360 align:middle line:84%
Ben, Ben, do you think most
people are simply out of touch

00:05:49.360 --> 00:05:50.700 align:middle line:90%
with nature?

00:05:50.700 --> 00:05:51.700 align:middle line:90%
>>STEWART: I believe so.

00:05:51.700 --> 00:05:55.690 align:middle line:84%
And I think that culture
and our economic climate

00:05:55.690 --> 00:05:57.940 align:middle line:84%
really makes a lot of things
fascinating that aren't

00:05:57.940 --> 00:05:59.030 align:middle line:90%
a part of nature anymore.

00:05:59.030 --> 00:06:02.110 align:middle line:84%
We're marveling in
our own creations,

00:06:02.110 --> 00:06:05.950 align:middle line:84%
and forgetting about the
rich dynamics of nature--

00:06:05.950 --> 00:06:07.660 align:middle line:90%
which isn't negative per se.

00:06:07.660 --> 00:06:11.080 align:middle line:84%
But when we get lost in that
marveling of our own creations,

00:06:11.080 --> 00:06:13.255 align:middle line:84%
we forget about
the natural world.

00:06:13.255 --> 00:06:14.570 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: When you got sick--

00:06:14.570 --> 00:06:16.870 align:middle line:84%
and if you don't want
to talk about it,

00:06:16.870 --> 00:06:20.282 align:middle line:84%
specifically, let me know--
but what happened to you?

00:06:20.282 --> 00:06:21.970 align:middle line:90%
>>STEWART: Oh, man.

00:06:21.970 --> 00:06:26.710 align:middle line:84%
Basically, this was exactly
when I met my fiancee.

00:06:26.710 --> 00:06:29.560 align:middle line:84%
And I was actually doing
a tour through Europe.

00:06:29.560 --> 00:06:31.090 align:middle line:90%
And that was how I met her.

00:06:31.090 --> 00:06:34.480 align:middle line:84%
And I think I just wore
my body down a lot.

00:06:34.480 --> 00:06:36.160 align:middle line:90%
I wasn't taking care of myself.

00:06:36.160 --> 00:06:37.660 align:middle line:90%
I was living at the extremes.

00:06:37.660 --> 00:06:39.310 align:middle line:90%
I was partying a lot.

00:06:39.310 --> 00:06:42.820 align:middle line:84%
And I lost about 25
pounds in seven days.

00:06:42.820 --> 00:06:45.070 align:middle line:90%
I was bedridden in Europe.

00:06:45.070 --> 00:06:49.210 align:middle line:84%
And so that's how things kind
of broke down in my life.

00:06:49.210 --> 00:06:52.270 align:middle line:90%
But I also thought that--

00:06:52.270 --> 00:06:54.640 align:middle line:84%
I had crazy ideas of
what I was actually

00:06:54.640 --> 00:06:57.610 align:middle line:84%
dealing with at the time,
like what my illness was.

00:06:57.610 --> 00:06:59.680 align:middle line:84%
And that was at
the point where I

00:06:59.680 --> 00:07:02.920 align:middle line:84%
realized that I hadn't been
treating myself correctly.

00:07:02.920 --> 00:07:05.440 align:middle line:84%
I hadn't been actually
loving this thing.

00:07:05.440 --> 00:07:08.840 align:middle line:84%
I'd been using it as a
tool for gratification.

00:07:08.840 --> 00:07:10.396 align:middle line:84%
So that was my
divorce from nature.

00:07:10.396 --> 00:07:11.770 align:middle line:84%
And that was,
really, the impetus

00:07:11.770 --> 00:07:14.500 align:middle line:84%
that started leading
me into the health

00:07:14.500 --> 00:07:16.210 align:middle line:90%
that I'm getting into now.

00:07:16.210 --> 00:07:18.580 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Had you
continued on that course,

00:07:18.580 --> 00:07:20.036 align:middle line:90%
would you have died?

00:07:20.036 --> 00:07:21.160 align:middle line:90%
>>STEWART: I'm pretty sure.

00:07:21.160 --> 00:07:23.326 align:middle line:90%
Either that, or I'd be--

00:07:23.326 --> 00:07:24.950 align:middle line:84%
I love Charlie Sheen--
but I'd probably

00:07:24.950 --> 00:07:28.570 align:middle line:84%
be like looking a lot older
and just a lot more beat

00:07:28.570 --> 00:07:31.540 align:middle line:84%
up by life, in the way
that you see Charlie

00:07:31.540 --> 00:07:33.040 align:middle line:90%
Sheen in the past five years.

00:07:33.040 --> 00:07:34.520 align:middle line:90%
His face has changed.

00:07:34.520 --> 00:07:38.146 align:middle line:84%
And I think I would have
probably gone down that road.

00:07:38.146 --> 00:07:40.270 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: If you had that
chance to talk to Charlie,

00:07:40.270 --> 00:07:42.460 align:middle line:90%
what would you tell him?

00:07:42.460 --> 00:07:44.245 align:middle line:90%
Smack him in the head?

00:07:44.245 --> 00:07:45.310 align:middle line:90%
>>STEWART: No.

00:07:45.310 --> 00:07:48.280 align:middle line:84%
Mainly, I would ask him
the right questions--

00:07:48.280 --> 00:07:49.810 align:middle line:90%
you know, what do you value?

00:07:49.810 --> 00:07:51.250 align:middle line:84%
What is it that
you really value?

00:07:51.250 --> 00:07:53.041 align:middle line:84%
And what are you trying
to get out of life?

00:07:53.041 --> 00:07:54.790 align:middle line:84%
Because maybe he's
on the exact path

00:07:54.790 --> 00:07:56.980 align:middle line:90%
that he needs or wants to be.

00:07:56.980 --> 00:08:00.910 align:middle line:84%
But I had to come to the
understanding that that path--

00:08:00.910 --> 00:08:02.660 align:middle line:90%
you know, I was in a rock band.

00:08:02.660 --> 00:08:06.300 align:middle line:84%
So although being at
a party late night--

00:08:06.300 --> 00:08:09.639 align:middle line:84%
all the drugs and the sex and
the alcohol that are around.

00:08:09.639 --> 00:08:11.305 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You abused
yourself, basically.

00:08:11.305 --> 00:08:11.650 align:middle line:90%
>>STEWART: I did.

00:08:11.650 --> 00:08:12.760 align:middle line:90%
I really abused myself.

00:08:12.760 --> 00:08:16.002 align:middle line:84%
And I needed to divorce
myself from what I was doing.

00:08:16.002 --> 00:08:18.460 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Do you find that there
are individuals in our life

00:08:18.460 --> 00:08:21.910 align:middle line:84%
that can help us or
prevent us from reaching

00:08:21.910 --> 00:08:25.434 align:middle line:90%
these goals that we're after?

00:08:25.434 --> 00:08:26.350 align:middle line:90%
>>STEWART: Absolutely.

00:08:26.350 --> 00:08:29.280 align:middle line:84%
You know, I think that
you can look out--

00:08:29.280 --> 00:08:30.730 align:middle line:90%
you don't need to find a guru.

00:08:30.730 --> 00:08:33.720 align:middle line:84%
Your next-door neighbor probably
has the same amount of wisdom.

00:08:33.720 --> 00:08:35.030 align:middle line:90%
They've lived their life.

00:08:35.030 --> 00:08:37.510 align:middle line:84%
And, yes, there are
forces that keep us down.

00:08:37.510 --> 00:08:40.790 align:middle line:84%
There are the economic elite,
and the hidden priesthoods

00:08:40.790 --> 00:08:41.590 align:middle line:90%
above them.

00:08:41.590 --> 00:08:44.290 align:middle line:90%
And I get into them in my films.

00:08:44.290 --> 00:08:46.630 align:middle line:84%
But I started to
realize that none of us

00:08:46.630 --> 00:08:48.390 align:middle line:84%
really know these
economic elites.

00:08:48.390 --> 00:08:49.746 align:middle line:90%
We read books about them.

00:08:49.746 --> 00:08:51.370 align:middle line:84%
We may have met them
a couple of times.

00:08:51.370 --> 00:08:53.750 align:middle line:90%
But we play in different groups.

00:08:53.750 --> 00:08:56.560 align:middle line:84%
So I was into conspiracy,
and I was pointing my fingers

00:08:56.560 --> 00:08:57.490 align:middle line:90%
at them a lot.

00:08:57.490 --> 00:08:59.080 align:middle line:84%
Until I started
realizing that there

00:08:59.080 --> 00:09:02.020 align:middle line:84%
was three fingers
pointing right back at me.

00:09:02.020 --> 00:09:04.132 align:middle line:84%
We need to start looking
at our own potential

00:09:04.132 --> 00:09:05.590 align:middle line:84%
and what we can
bring to the table,

00:09:05.590 --> 00:09:09.025 align:middle line:84%
rather than saying they need
to change their behavior.

00:09:09.025 --> 00:09:12.010 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: When we talk about
the terms super-humans,

00:09:12.010 --> 00:09:14.410 align:middle line:90%
what does that mean to you?

00:09:14.410 --> 00:09:15.940 align:middle line:84%
>>STEWART: Basically,
that means--

00:09:15.940 --> 00:09:18.880 align:middle line:84%
it's nothing above
and beyond science.

00:09:18.880 --> 00:09:20.620 align:middle line:84%
You know, it can seem
very comic booky.

00:09:20.620 --> 00:09:22.078 align:middle line:84%
And I kind of like
that, because it

00:09:22.078 --> 00:09:24.070 align:middle line:84%
allows us to go beyond
what we allow ourselves

00:09:24.070 --> 00:09:26.140 align:middle line:90%
to believe about our potential.

00:09:26.140 --> 00:09:28.720 align:middle line:84%
But it's nothing
that's beyond science.

00:09:28.720 --> 00:09:32.200 align:middle line:84%
It's just a highly optimized
and elevated human being

00:09:32.200 --> 00:09:33.080 align:middle line:90%
in all levels.

00:09:33.080 --> 00:09:36.370 align:middle line:84%
So that means in our diet,
in our movement habits,

00:09:36.370 --> 00:09:38.830 align:middle line:84%
and in the ways that
we focus our mind.

00:09:38.830 --> 00:09:40.330 align:middle line:84%
And then putting
them all together

00:09:40.330 --> 00:09:42.722 align:middle line:84%
in support of an
intention that we have

00:09:42.722 --> 00:09:43.930 align:middle line:90%
to carry forth with our life.

00:09:43.930 --> 00:09:44.355 align:middle line:90%


00:09:44.355 --> 00:09:46.480 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Ever since I've
been doing "Beyond Belief"

00:09:46.480 --> 00:09:48.020 align:middle line:90%
here on Gaia--

00:09:48.020 --> 00:09:49.930 align:middle line:84%
kicked my personal
life into high gear

00:09:49.930 --> 00:09:53.840 align:middle line:84%
as well, in terms of trying
to take care of yourself.

00:09:53.840 --> 00:09:56.530 align:middle line:84%
We're only on this
planet for a short term.

00:09:56.530 --> 00:09:58.590 align:middle line:84%
And you might as well make
it the most effective,

00:09:58.590 --> 00:10:00.280 align:middle line:90%
the best way you can.

00:10:00.280 --> 00:10:03.330 align:middle line:84%
And I started doing
all kinds of things--

00:10:03.330 --> 00:10:08.260 align:middle line:84%
some meditation; yoga-type
practices within myself;

00:10:08.260 --> 00:10:10.630 align:middle line:84%
supplements; watching
what you eat.

00:10:10.630 --> 00:10:12.130 align:middle line:90%
I'll slip once in a while.

00:10:12.130 --> 00:10:14.710 align:middle line:84%
I'll order a pizza
like the next person.

00:10:14.710 --> 00:10:18.520 align:middle line:84%
But I really have
downplayed things like that.

00:10:18.520 --> 00:10:20.530 align:middle line:84%
And it's made a
great difference.

00:10:20.530 --> 00:10:24.880 align:middle line:84%
Plus I'm trying to surround
myself around positive people,

00:10:24.880 --> 00:10:26.050 align:middle line:90%
not negativity.

00:10:26.050 --> 00:10:28.850 align:middle line:84%
Did you find that negative
people in your life

00:10:28.850 --> 00:10:29.650 align:middle line:90%
pulled you down?

00:10:29.650 --> 00:10:30.224 align:middle line:90%


00:10:30.224 --> 00:10:31.390 align:middle line:90%
>>STEWART: Yeah, absolutely.

00:10:31.390 --> 00:10:33.700 align:middle line:84%
And that's, partly,
because I didn't

00:10:33.700 --> 00:10:35.680 align:middle line:90%
have my sovereignty, in a way.

00:10:35.680 --> 00:10:38.440 align:middle line:84%
Because, you know, I think
if we were truly sovereign

00:10:38.440 --> 00:10:40.780 align:middle line:84%
and in our
super-human potential,

00:10:40.780 --> 00:10:42.820 align:middle line:84%
we'd be able to see the
people who are suffering

00:10:42.820 --> 00:10:47.170 align:middle line:84%
and their negativity, and be
able to disassociate ourselves

00:10:47.170 --> 00:10:49.150 align:middle line:84%
from it, but still
be able to help out.

00:10:49.150 --> 00:10:53.230 align:middle line:84%
But, yes, I was in a band, so
I was constantly around that.

00:10:53.230 --> 00:10:55.780 align:middle line:84%
So I was, in a sense, a
victim of that environment.

00:10:55.780 --> 00:10:58.810 align:middle line:84%
And it wasn't until I removed
myself from it that I started

00:10:58.810 --> 00:11:01.420 align:middle line:84%
realizing that everyone
who's in bands--

00:11:01.420 --> 00:11:04.810 align:middle line:84%
they eat gas station food;
they're sitting in a van

00:11:04.810 --> 00:11:05.674 align:middle line:90%
for 10--

00:11:05.674 --> 00:11:05.968 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: No exercise.

00:11:05.968 --> 00:11:07.180 align:middle line:90%
>>STEWART: --11 Hours a days.

00:11:07.180 --> 00:11:08.050 align:middle line:90%
No exercise.

00:11:08.050 --> 00:11:11.080 align:middle line:84%
And sedentary is
the new smoking.

00:11:11.080 --> 00:11:13.160 align:middle line:90%
Sitting is the new smoking.

00:11:13.160 --> 00:11:15.580 align:middle line:84%
So it's very nice to hear that
you've been doing all that,

00:11:15.580 --> 00:11:18.680 align:middle line:84%
because, really,
slipping up is great.

00:11:18.680 --> 00:11:19.480 align:middle line:90%
That's fine.

00:11:19.480 --> 00:11:22.420 align:middle line:84%
Because it gives us those
reference points of where

00:11:22.420 --> 00:11:25.030 align:middle line:90%
we've-- how far we've come--

00:11:25.030 --> 00:11:26.920 align:middle line:84%
as long as we keep
the trajectory

00:11:26.920 --> 00:11:30.370 align:middle line:84%
going towards elevating
our human potential.

00:11:30.370 --> 00:11:32.620 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What's interesting,
too, is when you slip up,

00:11:32.620 --> 00:11:35.950 align:middle line:84%
whether it's not working
out when you're supposed to;

00:11:35.950 --> 00:11:38.590 align:middle line:84%
or not taking the right
intake of supplements;

00:11:38.590 --> 00:11:41.740 align:middle line:84%
or not eating the
right foods; you really

00:11:41.740 --> 00:11:44.830 align:middle line:84%
feel guilty about it, like
you're cheating yourself,

00:11:44.830 --> 00:11:47.320 align:middle line:84%
that you've done
something wrong.

00:11:47.320 --> 00:11:49.360 align:middle line:90%
And I kind of like that feeling.

00:11:49.360 --> 00:11:51.490 align:middle line:84%
>>STEWART: It makes us
value what it is that we're

00:11:51.490 --> 00:11:52.600 align:middle line:90%
doing throughout the day.

00:11:52.600 --> 00:11:54.160 align:middle line:84%
I always go back
to our ancestors,

00:11:54.160 --> 00:11:57.080 align:middle line:84%
because they didn't look
at anything as working out.

00:11:57.080 --> 00:12:00.340 align:middle line:84%
They moved 10 to 15
miles a day just to eat.

00:12:00.340 --> 00:12:01.950 align:middle line:90%
So even in their diet--

00:12:01.950 --> 00:12:04.960 align:middle line:84%
diet wasn't just the food
that you fit in your mouth.

00:12:04.960 --> 00:12:07.430 align:middle line:84%
It was connected to every
other activity going on

00:12:07.430 --> 00:12:08.230 align:middle line:90%
throughout the day.

00:12:08.230 --> 00:12:12.310 align:middle line:84%
They would squat, foraging
for plants for 12 hours a day.

00:12:12.310 --> 00:12:14.860 align:middle line:84%
You can hardly find somebody
who can squat for two

00:12:14.860 --> 00:12:16.495 align:middle line:90%
to five minutes nowadays.

00:12:16.495 --> 00:12:17.295 align:middle line:90%
So--

00:12:17.295 --> 00:12:18.515 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And get up.

00:12:18.515 --> 00:12:19.820 align:middle line:90%
>>STEWART: Yeah, exactly.

00:12:19.820 --> 00:12:22.090 align:middle line:84%
And there was also
this great reverence.

00:12:22.090 --> 00:12:24.790 align:middle line:84%
They would have to bring all
this food back to their camp

00:12:24.790 --> 00:12:26.860 align:middle line:84%
and everyone would
celebrate the food.

00:12:26.860 --> 00:12:31.240 align:middle line:84%
So diet meant more than just
going to the grocery store--

00:12:31.240 --> 00:12:34.450 align:middle line:84%
no problem solving up here,
no problem solving down there.

00:12:34.450 --> 00:12:36.220 align:middle line:84%
But they used to have
to utilize the body

00:12:36.220 --> 00:12:37.660 align:middle line:90%
and mind in order to eat.

00:12:37.660 --> 00:12:39.580 align:middle line:84%
And they understood
that this food was

00:12:39.580 --> 00:12:41.050 align:middle line:90%
part of the great web of life.

00:12:41.050 --> 00:12:43.660 align:middle line:84%
What I've gotten into
is the connectivity

00:12:43.660 --> 00:12:47.920 align:middle line:84%
of our movement and our eating
and how to focus the mind.

00:12:47.920 --> 00:12:51.280 align:middle line:84%
And, really, the more we use
the body, the less our mind

00:12:51.280 --> 00:12:52.582 align:middle line:90%
really needs to take over.

00:12:52.582 --> 00:12:54.040 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Who would
you say might be

00:12:54.040 --> 00:12:57.970 align:middle line:84%
some of the super humans
on this planet today?

00:12:57.970 --> 00:13:01.990 align:middle line:84%
My example would be someone
like Sylvester Stallone, who

00:13:01.990 --> 00:13:03.935 align:middle line:90%
looks great for his age.

00:13:03.935 --> 00:13:05.110 align:middle line:90%
>>STEWART: Yeah, absolutely.

00:13:05.110 --> 00:13:06.568 align:middle line:84%
You know, I think
these people that

00:13:06.568 --> 00:13:10.970 align:middle line:84%
have the seed of the
super-humanism in there.

00:13:10.970 --> 00:13:15.130 align:middle line:84%
Because, mainly, my definition
of the super-human--

00:13:15.130 --> 00:13:18.790 align:middle line:84%
it goes beyond just the ambition
to work out and look good

00:13:18.790 --> 00:13:20.330 align:middle line:90%
and optimize your health.

00:13:20.330 --> 00:13:22.852 align:middle line:84%
It has to go into what are
we doing for the planet.

00:13:22.852 --> 00:13:24.310 align:middle line:84%
I don't believe
that I was put here

00:13:24.310 --> 00:13:28.520 align:middle line:84%
on this planet just to look
good and to gratify myself.

00:13:28.520 --> 00:13:32.050 align:middle line:84%
So when I look at what
do I have to offer,

00:13:32.050 --> 00:13:33.380 align:middle line:90%
I'm optimizing myself--

00:13:33.380 --> 00:13:36.220 align:middle line:84%
not for myself,
but for my daughter

00:13:36.220 --> 00:13:38.512 align:middle line:84%
and for future
generations to come.

00:13:38.512 --> 00:13:39.970 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Ben, in
one of your films,

00:13:39.970 --> 00:13:43.780 align:middle line:84%
"Waking Infinity," you talk
about the incredible piercing

00:13:43.780 --> 00:13:46.285 align:middle line:90%
of the four-minute mile.

00:13:46.285 --> 00:13:49.810 align:middle line:84%
>>STEWART: Prior to 1954,
people overwhelmingly agreed

00:13:49.810 --> 00:13:52.540 align:middle line:84%
that the human body was
not capable of running

00:13:52.540 --> 00:13:54.200 align:middle line:90%
a four-minute mile.

00:13:54.200 --> 00:13:57.310 align:middle line:84%
Our bone structure is not
built for it, they said.

00:13:57.310 --> 00:14:00.430 align:middle line:84%
Our lungs cannot handle
it, they claimed.

00:14:00.430 --> 00:14:03.490 align:middle line:84%
However, on May 6 of that
year, Roger Bannister

00:14:03.490 --> 00:14:07.180 align:middle line:84%
ran a mile in 0.6 seconds
under four minutes.

00:14:07.180 --> 00:14:10.450 align:middle line:84%
John Landry's best
attempt, prior to 1954,

00:14:10.450 --> 00:14:12.804 align:middle line:84%
was a four-minute
and two-second mile.

00:14:12.804 --> 00:14:14.470 align:middle line:84%
He made a statement
that the four minute

00:14:14.470 --> 00:14:18.100 align:middle line:84%
mile was a brick wall that
can not be penetrated.

00:14:18.100 --> 00:14:20.350 align:middle line:84%
He claimed he would never
attempt to beat it again.

00:14:20.350 --> 00:14:24.130 align:middle line:84%
56 days after Bannister
broke through that wall,

00:14:24.130 --> 00:14:27.160 align:middle line:84%
Landry was inspired
to try again.

00:14:27.160 --> 00:14:29.650 align:middle line:84%
His very next attempt
broke Bannister's record

00:14:29.650 --> 00:14:31.656 align:middle line:90%
by 1 and 1/2 seconds.

00:14:31.656 --> 00:14:36.830 align:middle line:84%
The following year, 37 runners
broke the four-minute mile.

00:14:36.830 --> 00:14:41.840 align:middle line:84%
The year after that, 300
runners broke through that wall.

00:14:41.840 --> 00:14:45.110 align:middle line:84%
The wall was not made of
brick, as Landry said.

00:14:45.110 --> 00:14:47.375 align:middle line:90%
It was made of belief.

00:14:47.375 --> 00:14:49.490 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What an
amazing segment.

00:14:49.490 --> 00:14:51.860 align:middle line:84%
Why was the
chronology like that?

00:14:51.860 --> 00:14:54.890 align:middle line:84%
We go years without
a four-minute mile.

00:14:54.890 --> 00:14:56.660 align:middle line:90%
Then one person does it.

00:14:56.660 --> 00:14:58.520 align:middle line:90%
Then another person does it.

00:14:58.520 --> 00:14:59.780 align:middle line:90%
Then 30 people do it.

00:14:59.780 --> 00:15:01.730 align:middle line:90%
Then 300 people do it.

00:15:01.730 --> 00:15:04.400 align:middle line:84%
What made that chronology
happen the way it did?

00:15:04.400 --> 00:15:07.190 align:middle line:84%
>>STEWART: It's
belief, honestly.

00:15:07.190 --> 00:15:10.130 align:middle line:84%
Belief and hard work, but
it all starts with belief.

00:15:10.130 --> 00:15:12.500 align:middle line:84%
And that's why I love the
title of this show, "Beyond

00:15:12.500 --> 00:15:15.860 align:middle line:84%
Belief," because going
beyond the belief

00:15:15.860 --> 00:15:17.480 align:middle line:84%
limits that we set
for ourselves--

00:15:17.480 --> 00:15:18.830 align:middle line:90%
you see what happens.

00:15:18.830 --> 00:15:22.250 align:middle line:84%
Doctors, scientists, everybody
was saying, it's impossible.

00:15:22.250 --> 00:15:23.150 align:middle line:90%
The body--

00:15:23.150 --> 00:15:23.691 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Can't do it.

00:15:23.691 --> 00:15:25.566 align:middle line:84%
>>STEWART: --its technology
just can't do it.

00:15:25.566 --> 00:15:28.810 align:middle line:84%
But as soon as one person did
it, people started training.

00:15:28.810 --> 00:15:31.790 align:middle line:90%
And within two years, over 300--

00:15:31.790 --> 00:15:33.440 align:middle line:90%
maybe close to 400 people--

00:15:33.440 --> 00:15:35.160 align:middle line:90%
had done it at that point.

00:15:35.160 --> 00:15:38.420 align:middle line:84%
And so that really just
shows us that the peak

00:15:38.420 --> 00:15:41.900 align:middle line:84%
of human potential
does not end here.

00:15:41.900 --> 00:15:43.400 align:middle line:90%
And it, possibly, doesn't end.

00:15:43.400 --> 00:15:46.745 align:middle line:84%
It just is governed by the
amount of belief we have.

00:15:46.745 --> 00:15:48.770 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And how strong
can that belief be?

00:15:48.770 --> 00:15:53.580 align:middle line:84%
Can it be as big and as
broad as you can make it?

00:15:53.580 --> 00:15:54.580 align:middle line:90%
>>STEWART: I believe so.

00:15:54.580 --> 00:15:57.470 align:middle line:84%
But I also believe that we're
not meant for one person

00:15:57.470 --> 00:16:00.020 align:middle line:90%
to just skyrocket into that.

00:16:00.020 --> 00:16:02.530 align:middle line:84%
Because we'd be mowed down
like the tallest poppy,

00:16:02.530 --> 00:16:05.150 align:middle line:84%
due to the powers
that be on the planet.

00:16:05.150 --> 00:16:08.450 align:middle line:84%
So I believe that we
also help each other,

00:16:08.450 --> 00:16:10.800 align:middle line:84%
we lift each other
up in these ways.

00:16:10.800 --> 00:16:13.760 align:middle line:84%
So, again, I mean,
it could possibly--

00:16:13.760 --> 00:16:16.110 align:middle line:90%
I believe it can go on forever.

00:16:16.110 --> 00:16:19.287 align:middle line:84%
But I don't really have any
evidence to back that up.

00:16:19.287 --> 00:16:20.870 align:middle line:84%
So I'll just stay
with what I do know.

00:16:20.870 --> 00:16:22.970 align:middle line:90%
I know that we consistently--

00:16:22.970 --> 00:16:25.100 align:middle line:84%
throughout the
lifeline of humanity--

00:16:25.100 --> 00:16:29.180 align:middle line:84%
we consistently break
these imaginary boundaries

00:16:29.180 --> 00:16:29.980 align:middle line:90%
that we have.

00:16:29.980 --> 00:16:32.780 align:middle line:84%
And I think that's because,
as soon as we break

00:16:32.780 --> 00:16:35.510 align:middle line:84%
beyond that belief,
our mind starts

00:16:35.510 --> 00:16:39.545 align:middle line:84%
to tell the body how to adapt
to what our intention is.

00:16:39.545 --> 00:16:40.920 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: We know,
as people, Ben,

00:16:40.920 --> 00:16:45.210 align:middle line:84%
that when we're in the groove
we can't get out of it,

00:16:45.210 --> 00:16:48.830 align:middle line:84%
that everything seems
to be working for us.

00:16:48.830 --> 00:16:50.840 align:middle line:84%
Do you feel that way,
too, sometimes-- you just

00:16:50.840 --> 00:16:52.470 align:middle line:90%
know you're in the groove?

00:16:52.470 --> 00:16:53.270 align:middle line:90%
>>STEWART: Yeah.

00:16:53.270 --> 00:16:55.640 align:middle line:84%
Actually, there is
great terminology

00:16:55.640 --> 00:16:58.310 align:middle line:84%
that's being thrown on that--
that's called the flow state.

00:16:58.310 --> 00:17:00.710 align:middle line:90%
And I'm really into flow arts--

00:17:00.710 --> 00:17:02.880 align:middle line:84%
a lot of spinning
and things like that.

00:17:02.880 --> 00:17:06.980 align:middle line:84%
But the flow state, for the most
part, really has to do with--

00:17:06.980 --> 00:17:10.550 align:middle line:84%
whether it's extreme sports or
whether it's public speaking

00:17:10.550 --> 00:17:12.319 align:middle line:84%
or-- doesn't matter
what you're doing.

00:17:12.319 --> 00:17:13.289 align:middle line:90%
It really means--

00:17:13.289 --> 00:17:14.089 align:middle line:90%
I move in nature.

00:17:14.089 --> 00:17:14.983 align:middle line:90%
I climb trees and I--

00:17:14.983 --> 00:17:15.783 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It clicks.

00:17:15.783 --> 00:17:16.980 align:middle line:90%
You know it's clicking.

00:17:16.980 --> 00:17:17.780 align:middle line:90%
>>STEWART: Yeah.

00:17:17.780 --> 00:17:23.569 align:middle line:84%
So, basically, when the brain
down-regulates and you're not

00:17:23.569 --> 00:17:25.910 align:middle line:84%
over-thinking, you still
have an intelligence

00:17:25.910 --> 00:17:29.299 align:middle line:84%
of the body that can solve
problems really immediately.

00:17:29.299 --> 00:17:31.340 align:middle line:84%
And that's what you start
learning-- people doing

00:17:31.340 --> 00:17:32.952 align:middle line:90%
Parkour and these fancy tricks.

00:17:32.952 --> 00:17:34.910 align:middle line:84%
And they're jumping over
things, and they don't

00:17:34.910 --> 00:17:36.159 align:middle line:90%
know what's on the other side.

00:17:36.159 --> 00:17:39.050 align:middle line:84%
So they immediately have to
adapt to the environment.

00:17:39.050 --> 00:17:40.730 align:middle line:84%
That, to me, is the
ultimate readiness

00:17:40.730 --> 00:17:43.451 align:middle line:84%
that we should be in in
this state of affairs

00:17:43.451 --> 00:17:44.825 align:middle line:84%
that we have on
the planet today.

00:17:44.825 --> 00:17:47.840 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What importance
would you put in diet

00:17:47.840 --> 00:17:49.385 align:middle line:90%
in the scheme of things?

00:17:49.385 --> 00:17:50.635 align:middle line:90%
>>STEWART: One of the biggest.

00:17:50.635 --> 00:17:52.820 align:middle line:84%
